description: Prefer expression-bodied members (=>) for trivial methods, properties, ctors, and operators.
globs: "**/*.cs"
alwaysApply: false
---

# Expression-bodied members

When a method, property, indexer, constructor, finalizer, or operator is a **single expression**, use the **expression-bodied** form (`=>`).

## Preferred

```csharp
public string FullName => $"{First} {Last}";

public bool IsExpired() => Clock.UtcNow >= ExpiresAt;

public Task<Tenant> GetAsync(Guid id) => _repo.LoadAsync(id);

public override string ToString() => $"Tenant({Id})";

public static AlertSeverity From(int score) => score switch
{
    >= 90 => AlertSeverity.Critical,
    >= 70 => AlertSeverity.High,
    >= 40 => AlertSeverity.Medium,
    _     => AlertSeverity.Low
};
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid
public string FullName
{
    get
    {
        return $"{First} {Last}";
    }
}

public bool IsExpired()
{
    return Clock.UtcNow >= ExpiresAt;
}
```

## Scope

- Use `=>` only when the body is **one** expression (a `switch` expression counts).
- Stay with a block body when there are multiple statements, local variables, `try`/`catch`, or in-method comments needed.
- Each member still goes in **its own file** per the project rule.
- Consistent with **`CSharp-SimpleProperties-OneLine.mdc`** for the auto-property case.
